<subSubSection id="C2DF6529F32DFFE3FF15F979FC006326" pageId="20" pageNumber="19" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8A7A36A2F32DFFE3FF15F979FC006326" blockId="20.[192,1440,1728,1817]" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F32DFFE3FF15F979FED662E7" bold="true" box="[192,335,1728,1752]" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="4DC54D21F32DFFE3FCE6F979FBAF62E8" authorityName="Flowers" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Bechyne" baseAuthorityYear="2018" box="[819,1078,1728,1751]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angustomarginata">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F32DFFE3FCE6F979FBAF62E8" box="[819,1078,1728,1751]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">B. angustomarginata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the small pair of tubercles on sternite VII in the female. This character is shared with 
<taxonomicName id="4DC54D21F32DFFE3FC5AF958FBDC62C7" authorityName="Flowers" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Flowers" baseAuthorityYear="2018" box="[911,1093,1760,1784]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chiriquensis">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F32DFFE3FC5AF958FBDC62C7" box="[911,1093,1760,1784]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">B. chiriquensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the characteristic lightcolored tarsi of 
<taxonomicName id="4DC54D21F32DFFE3FEA9F8BBFDAA6326" authorityName="Flowers" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Flowers" baseAuthorityYear="2018" box="[380,563,1793,1817]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chiriquensis">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F32DFFE3FEA9F8BBFDAA6326" box="[380,563,1793,1817]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">B. chiriquensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
will distinguish that species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C2DF6529F32DFFE3FF15F896FC1863B6" pageId="20" pageNumber="19" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8A7A36A2F32DFFE3FF15F896FC1863B6" blockId="20.[192,1440,1839,1929]" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F32DFFE3FF15F896FEDA6378" bold="true" box="[192,323,1839,1863]" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">Remarks.</emphasis>
The male can be distinguished from other species with “arrowhead”-shaped median lobes by the relatively weak patches of spicules at the tip of the endophallus. 
<taxonomicName id="4DC54D21F32DFFE3FBFAF8F6FB6D6358" authorityName="Bechyne" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Bechyne" baseAuthorityYear="1950" box="[1071,1268,1871,1895]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="placidula">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F32DFFE3FBFAF8F6FB6D6358" box="[1071,1268,1871,1895]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">Beltia placidula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distributed through the Amazonian region of northern 
<collectingCountry id="F2D27632F32DFFE3FD04F8C8FC9563B7" box="[721,780,1905,1928]" name="Peru" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">Peru</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="12FE2A27F32DFFE3FCC9F8C9FCED63B6" box="[796,884,1904,1929]" captionStart="Figures 78–79" captionStartId="43.[191,286,1850,1872]" captionTargetBox="[192,1441,412,1699]" captionTargetId="figure@43.[189,1443,412,1702]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="Figures 78–79. Distribution maps for Beltia spp. 78) Northwestern South America: B. confusa (star), B. gorgona (inverted triangles), B. placidula (blue circles), B. rugosa (red circle), B. weyrauchi (square). 79) Ecuador: B. awapita (hexagon), B. ledesmae (squares), B. napoensis (triangles), B. talaga (circle), B. tsachila (star)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3713527" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3713527/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="19">Fig. 78</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
